Amy, <br><br>
The words above are written by individuals that served in Vietnam, they say a lot and reflect much of what we all feel.<br><br>
Many felt the wall did not reflect honor to the Vietnam Veterans especially since it had been designed by Maya Lin an Asian American. <br>
Since then much has changed, and what is really surprising is the over all profound impact that wall has had on anyone visiting it. There is a solemn respect and honor present there that cannot be explained with words of this world.<br>
I have visited the wall twice, while I was in Washington lobbying Congress. I didn’t know how I would react, I was not expecting the tears to flow as they did. I could not stop them, It made no difference then who built the wall, it was thereI found the names of Marines I had known in Vietnam some of which had died in my place. How can you not respect a site like that. <br>
Many Vietnam veterans have never taken the time to think through much of what transpired at that time.  History's shame (not the wall) has denied us the right to share those memories with our love ones and because of this the Vietnam Veteran wall was at first not fully accepted.<br><br>
 <br>
The following is from the end of a book, (currently being edited), Dreams of Glory: Clear Fields of Fire, © by Cook Barela 1997.<br><br>
ON MY WAY BACK<br>
June 26th, 1968, OKINAWA <br>
When I arrived at Okinawa, I ran into Benevedo and Bennet who were also on their way home. I hadn't seen them in thirteen months. They had served their tour of duty with the 3rd Marine Division near the DMZ, but that's another story, another diary that for now, remains written only in their hearts and minds. Perhaps one day they will share with us their fields of fire and their dreams of glory. <br>
We were the fortunate ones, the survivors.  No one else from our old 101 platoon series at MCRD made it back without being killed or seriously wounded. <br>
While I was in Vietnam I realized that I had made a difference.  There are Marines alive today that wouldn't be if I hadn't volunteered for duty, If I hadn't believed in my country and in what we were doing there. Ronald Allen Moore (Bro), gave his life when he volunteered in my place and today his name is etched on that black reflective wall in Washington, D.C. I had a chance to visit that wall a few years back and it had a profound effect on me. The tears I never shed in war, the love I never gave, the moments lost and pains and sorrows shared were all bottled up and released on that day. All Viet Nam veterans should experience such a healing and finally make peace with the past and move on toward the future....<br><br>
Feel free to contact me, Cook Barela<br>

